Since the tangent function has a period of $180^\circ$, we can subtract multiples of $180^\circ$ from $1000^\circ$ to obtain angles in the interval $(-90^\circ, 90^\circ)$.

Let $k$ be an integer such that $1000^\circ-180k^\circ$ is in the interval $(-90^\circ, 90^\circ)$.
To find $k$, we need to satisfy:

$$1000-180k \geq -90 \qquad \text{ and } \qquad 1000-180k \leq 90.$$Subtract $1000$ from both sides of each inequality: \begin{align*}
-180k &\geq-1090,\\ -180k &\leq-910.\end{align*}Divide both sides by $-180$: \begin{align*}
k&\leq 6.\overline{05},\\
k&\geq 5.0556\end{align*}Thus, the only integers $k$ satisfying the conditions are $k = 5, 6$.  However, for $k = 6$, we have \begin{align*}
1000-180\cdot 6 & = -80,\\
\frac{-80}{180} = \frac{-4}{9}.\end{align*}These is in interval ($90,-90$) of $(\tan \theta)$. Let’s test
$k = 5$: \begin{align*}
-80/180 &= -\text{0.4444}\\
800/180 &= \text{4.444}\\\tan n^\circ &=-\tan\text{ 25}.\end{align*}
The negative angle is $n^\circ = -(25)^\circ$, so $n$ equals $$-\text{0.4444}$$ and  \[\tan n^\circ=\tan \text{ 25}.\]

